<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-330-668  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 330 668.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  June 5 1989 v3 n23 p17(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Competition mavens meet incessantly seeking solutions. (InPerspective commentary on foreign competition issue)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Anthes, Gary H.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Symposiums dealing with the erosion of US technological leadershipare heavily attended by both federal agency officials and Fortune100 executives.andP;  But for all the analysis about foreign,particularly Japanese, competition, a sense of paralysis can bedetected.andP;  A number of immediate steps need to be taken to supportthe long range goal of leadership recovery.andP;  Investment in basictechnology can be stimulated through governmental actions such aslowering capital investment costs through tax law adjustments,pushing ahead with the completion of an interagency plan forestablishing a high-performance, high-bandwidth fiber opticnetwork linking research centers across the country and sponsoringan agency dedicated to the development and commercialization ofnon-defense technologies.andP;  Stricter control is needed withcountries that close markets to the US or engage in dumping andother unfair practices.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     National GovernmentCompaniesFuture of ComputingForeign CompetitionJapanese CompetitionTechnologyFiber OpticsGovernment FundingComputer Industry.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>